CLOSTRIDIUM DIFFICILE, RIBOTYPE 027 - UK (03): (SCOTLAND)
*********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 2 Jul 2008
Source: Health Protection Scotland (HPS) weekly report [edited]
<http://www.documents.hps.scot.nhs.uk/ewr/pdf2008/0827.pdf>


Quarterly report on the Surveillance of _Clostridium difficile_
Associated Disease (CDAD) in Scotland, January-March 2008
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Ribotype 027 outbreaks
----------------------
During the period from 22 Apr to 6 Jun 2008, outbreaks involving
ribotype 027 were reported from hospitals in Aberdeen, Glasgow, and
Clyde.

A total of 4 cases of 027 were reported from the Aberdeen Royal
Infirmary and 2 cases from Aberdeen Woodend Hospital. A total of 6
cases of 027 were reported from Stobhill Hospital, Glasgow. A total
of 4 cases of 027 were reported from the Vale of Leven Hospital. The
numbers mentioned here only include confirmed and typed cases at the
time of completion of this report.

Discussion
----------
This report covers CDAD [_Clostridium difficile_-associated disease]
surveillance data in persons, aged 65 and over, collected from
January-March 2008. Accumulated typing data is provided covering the
period from November 2007-March 2008. In addition, outbreaks that
occurred in April-May [2008] (outside the reporting period for this
report) are reported here as well due to the high public interest.

The recent outbreaks caused by ribotype 027 have tripled the total
number of 027 cases recorded in Scotland since 2006. Similar trends
have also been observed in Europe, where increased surveillance
activity has led to the identification of ribotype 027 in 16
countries.

Of the Scottish 027-isolates that have been MIC-tested, 100 percent
were resistant to fluoroquinolones, 90 percent to clindamycin, and
more than 50 percent resistant to cephalosporins. Thus, the use of
fluoroquinolones, cephalosporins, and clindamycin may play an
important role in the spread and persistence of ribotype 027 in
Scotland.

Moreover, isolates of ribotype 078 have been reported in Scotland.
Ribotype 078 is a new emerging type with similar mechanisms for hyper
production of toxins as ribotype 027. Ribotype 078 is increasingly
being reported in Belgium, The Netherlands, and Northern Ireland.
Ribotype 078 is a common ribotype in pigs.

[Byline: The HPS _C. difficile_ Working Group]

--
